user: Consider a harmonic oscillator in the ground state, verifying equal variance in the position \(x\) and the momentum \(p\), as dictated by the Heisenberg uncertainty relation. Find the standard deviation of \(x\) (in meters), which corresponds to the zero-point motion of a harmonic oscillator in its ground state, in terms of its mass \(m\) and its angular frequency \(\omega_m\).

To find the standard deviation of the position of a harmonic oscillator in the ground state, we first need to equate the variances of position and momentum using the Heisenberg uncertainty relation. The expression for the variance of position and momentum in the ground state can be obtained from the relation. After equating the variances, we get the expression for the angular frequency in terms of mass. Substituting the expression for the angular frequency in the expression for the variance of position, we obtain the standard deviation of position. The final expression for the standard deviation of position in terms of mass and angular frequency is:
\begin{equation}
\Delta x = \sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{2m\omega_m}} = \sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{m}} = \sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{m_e}} \approx 5.3 \times 10^{-11} \text{ m}
\end{equation}
where \(m_e\) is the mass of the electron.

